 until anyone provides me with specific examples or arguments, I'll continue to disregard that type of talk unworthy of any further attention.<br><br>Now, what has me most excited, and what hasn't really been discussed so far, is the Realm vs Realm combat aspect of DAoC.  This is basically PvP on steriods, but it's not such a part of the game that everyone has to participate in it.  For those who simply enjoy PvE combat similar to your basic EQ server, then they can level to 50 and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> never</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> have to fight against another human.  But, for those who want something grander and more challenging to do once they get into the upper levels, then RvR is where it's at.<br><br>In a nutshell, there are 3 Realms or teams - Albions, Midgards, and Hibernians.  These 3 teams are <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> completely</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> separated from one another.  They cannot communicate with each other at all, their classes and abilities are different, their spells and spell effects even have subtle differences.  Each team starts out in the own realm.  Imagine a 3-bladed airplane propeller.  Each realm will start out at the tips of each blade, and the closer you get to the middle, the closer you are to the frontier lands where most of the PvP combat will take place.<br><br>Forts can be seiged and captured, and realm artifacts that grant special powers to the team who controls them can be stolen.  Realm points are granted for stuff like the aforementioned things, and they can also be acquired by killing players from the opposing teams.  With realm points, people can purchase titles, houses, extra communication channels, and various other things.  Guilds can run their banners up the flagpoles of captured forts, while also wearing their guild crests on their cloaks and shields.  Volleys of arrows can be launched into the air and tracked the whole way down, (archery is actually a viable offense in DAoC) and seige equipment can be crafted by players and used to break down the doors protecting an opponents fort.  (I've also been told that one of the most fantastic things to see in the game is when groups of casters are launching spells at each other at night.  Just think of tons of EQ wizards launching low-level bolt spells - only these spell effects are <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> much</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> better looking - and you'll start to get the idea.)<br><br>So does DAoC stand a chance against EQ?  You're damn skippy it does.  Graphics don't mean jack squat in my book.  It's gameplay that matters, and any fan of games Diablo or Civilization can tell you that.  And to be honest, the graphics of Luclin don't impress me all that much.  When all is said and done, it's still EQ and the game itself has seen its best days.  Is DAoC going to be revolutionary?  Doubtful, but it <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> will</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> represent the next step in the evolution of the MMOLRPG. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEEFDE><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub18.ezboard.com/uslynstorm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SLynstorm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>MithMarr Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#006400>(8/31/01 11:31:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub18.ezboard.com/fmithanielmarrdailynewsfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=717.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: eyah</span><hr size=1> My experience with EQ has left me scared as hell of Luclin.  I figure it will take them months to get the servers stable again, and all this for better graphics i will have to shut down so as to not go LD everytime a group of more than 12 people are in my field of vision?  So 'Verass' can add more items for the loot whores to grab up like some sick drug, then see it sold in Freeport.<br>The game is rapidly losing my interest and the constant 